[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Kling is a 62-year-old gentleman who is referred for treatment of sigmoid colon cancer.  Mr. Kling had a four-month history of bright-red blood per rectum.  Flexible sigmoidoscopy March 23, 2010, was positive for a mass in the sigmoid.  He therefore underwent his first full colonoscopy March 25, 2010, which was positive for five lesions.  Two polyps measuring 3-mm and 6-mm were removed from the cecum (tubulovillous adenoma with low-grade dysplasia) and two polyps were removed from the descending colon measuring 2-mm and 4-mm (invasive grade 3 [of 4] adenocarcinoma and fragment of mucosal prolapse polyp on pathology).  A 5-cm large fungating mass was noted in the sigmoid colon which was biopsied and then tattooed on the proximal and distal margin.  Pathology of this lesion was invasive grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma as well, confirmed by Smith Medical Center.  CT abdomen and pelvis showed thickening of the entire left colon from the splenic flexure to sigmoid.  CEA was 1.2 on March 25, 2010.  The patient presents now for evaluation and surgical recommendations.
Comorbidities include hypertension, previously treated with Hytrin.  He has been off medication now for some time.  There is no history of a heart attack or stroke, bleeding disorder, or anesthesia reaction thrombosis, or glaucoma.  There is a question of sleep apnea.  Apparently, he has had a sleep study, and one physician felt he had sleep apnea and the other felt he did not.  He does not currently use a CPAP.  He offers no other health complaints.

